as throughout his career disrupts the existing canon of architectural history, which has focused on abrupt changes linked to individual ‘pioneers’, encouraging us to think again about who is studied in architectural history and how they are researched.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitectural criticismzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aArchitecture, Moderny20th century. 7aDESIGN / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aArchitectural Criticism.  aBrutalism.  aHubert De Cronin Hastings.  aJ.M. Richards.  aModern Architecture.  aNikolaus Pevsner.  aPeggy Angus.  aReyner Banham.  aThe Architectural Review.  aVernacular architecture.1 aKelly, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614376140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526143761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526143761/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles